From this it would seem that among the poems ascribed to Claudian were some in Greek, a ngantomachia, and an epigram on a crystal 5 and that there was also extant with the same ascription a poem on Mount Aetna, which Gyraldus had copied with his own hand from a correct and very ancient MS.‚ which was believed to have once been in the possession of Petrarch. He does not say that this was a MS. of Claudian ,· but this is a reasonable inference from his statement. For in all the earliest MSS. of the poem, whether entire or in excerptS, with which we are acquainted it is ascribed to Vergil, and to Vergil only: if therefore Gyraldus attributed it, though doubtfully, to Claudian, it must have been an inference from its inclusion in a volume containing other works of that poet.
